                <head>213. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 15, 1968, municipal elections were held in the Dominican Republic. Over 1
                    million people turned out to vote for candidates in 77 municipalities, 200,000
                    more than the Embassy had estimated. With the abstention of the left of center
                    Partido Revolucionario Dominicano(<gloss target="#t_PRD1">PRD</gloss>) and other
                    important right of center parties, it was expected that President <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJ1">Balaguer</persName>ʼs Party, the Partido Reformista (<gloss
                        target="#t_PR1">PR</gloss>), would win a majority of the votes. Of the 77
                    municipalities, Partido Reformista won 66 including Santo Domingo. The left of
                    center Partido Revolucionario Social Christiano (<gloss target="#t_PRSC1"
                        >PRSC</gloss>) won 2 municipalities and the approximately 45 local
                    independent political movements won 9.</p>
            </div>
